  fjs.parentNode.insertBefore(js, fjs);
}(document, 'script', 'facebook-jssdk'));</script>

<div class="fb-like" data-layout="button_count" data-action="like" data-show-faces="true" data-share="true"></div>

</td>

<td valign="top"><script type="text/javascript" src="http://w.sharethis.com/button/sharethis.js#publisher=af8ac4c7-faf4-4427-910c-d4f53c264a57&amp;type=website"></script></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
</div>
		<div class="contentDetailBody">
<span style="text-transform:uppercase;">By: Katie McKissick</span><BR>
April 23, 2013 &mdash; <table width="310" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="right">
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td align="right"><iframe width="300" scrolling="no" height="170" frameborder="0" src="http://www.syfy.com/_utils/video/embed.php?/videos/small/_vid2631456"></iframe></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>
            <h6 style="text-align: left;"><span style="line-height: 15px;">&nbsp; &nbsp;Watch full</span><span style="line-height: 15px;">&nbsp;episodes of Robot Combat League&nbsp;</span><a style="line-height: 15px; text-indent: 0px;" href="http://www.syfy.com/robotcombatleague/episodes">here</a><span style="line-height: 15px;">.</span></h6>
            </td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>When <a href="http://robotics.usc.edu/~rossmead/">Ross Mead</a> first got an email about a new TV show featuring fighting 8-foot-tall humanoid robots looking for robotics engineers, he didn&rsquo;t take it very seriously. <br />
<br />
But two years later, the 28-year-old Viterbi Ph.D. candidate in computer science became a contestant on that very show, <a href="http://www.syfy.com/robotcombatleague">Robot Combat League</a>&nbsp;on Syfy.</p>
<p>Created by USC alumnus Jeremy Whitham, Robot Combat League is a tournament where 12 teams of human-controlled robots fight in hand to hand combat.  Each team consists of a robotics expert serving as the &ldquo;robo-tech&rdquo; and a professional fighter serving as the &ldquo;robo-jockey.&rdquo;  The robo-jockeys are outfitted with sensor-laden exo-suits that translate their arm movements to the robot. The &ldquo;robo-tech&rdquo; controls the rest of the robot using throttles and joysticks, and is responsible for between-fight repairs and maintenance.</p>
<table width="580" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td>
            <p><img width="580" height="272" alt="RCLROSS 580" src="/assets/157/85478.png" /></p>
            </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>
            <h6 style="text-align: left;">USC Viterbi Ph.D. candidate, Ross Mead (left) and Andrew Montanez (right)</h6>
            </td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>Mead is a member of <a href="http://www.syfy.com/robotcombatleague/crews/a_x_e">team A.X.E.</a> along with professional mixed martial arts fighter Andrew Montanez. Their robot <a href="http://www.syfy.com/robotcombatleague/photos/meet_the_robots?id=1">A.X.E.</a> is 7 feet 10 inches tall, weighs 842 pounds and has a giant axe for a head. Other robots sport features such as steel armor, aluminum spikes and hand blades.</p>
<table width="160" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="left">
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><img width="150" height="233" alt="" src="/assets/157/85480.jpg" /></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>
            <h6>&nbsp;The A.X.E. Robot</h6>
            </td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>As the robots compete in the tournament, sparks fly, hydraulic fluid leaks and robots are cut in half. But for Mead, the spectacle is just a starting point.</p>
<p>&ldquo;To me, it&rsquo;s a platform to deliver a message. Robot Combat League was a fun thing to do, but the whole point was to get people excited about what&rsquo;s going on--get excited about robotics, get excited about technology.&rdquo;</p>
<p>And that&rsquo;s exactly what happened. As soon as the show premiered on Feb. 26, 2013 on Syfy, Mead started hearing from viewers. He now spends two hours each day responding to <a href="mailto:RossMead.RCL@gmail.com?subject=Robot%20Combat%20League">fan mail</a>--some from kids and some from parents eager to encourage their children&rsquo;s new interest in robotics.  Ross responds to such requests by sending the chapter he wrote for the book <i><a href="http://www.igi-global.com/book/robots-education-new-technology-learning/58277">Robots in K-12 Education: A New Technology for Learning</a></i>, entitled &ldquo;<a href="http://www.igi-global.com/chapter/grade-school-grad-school/63421">Grade School to Grad School: An Integrated STEM Pipeline Model through Robotics</a>.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mead also saw a dramatic increase in the views of his publications, including his research profile on <a href="http://usc.academia.edu/RossMead">Academia.edu</a>, a site that allows people to share information about their published research. &ldquo;I used to get just 5 or 6 views a week, but all of a sudden I was getting hundreds of views each week.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The Trojan Family was well represented on Robot Combat League &mdash; not only by Mead and the show&rsquo;s creator Whitham, but also by Viterbi alumnus George Kirkman, co-founder of <a href="http://rollingrobots.com/">Rolling Robots</a>, and Amanda Lucas, George Lucas&rsquo; daughter.</p>
<p>The show also featured a diverse mix of contestants. Of the 24 participants, 10 were female. This was important to Mead. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve done work trying to get more underrepresented groups, women in particular, in STEM--science, technology, engineering, and math,&rdquo; says Mead. &ldquo;The show had a really excellent balance of men and women. It was an opportunity for me to talk about those issues and highlight role models like [fellow contestants] Heather Knight and Annika O&rsquo;Brien.&rdquo;</p>
<p>For the seven weeks of filming, Mead felt as though he was living a double life (not entirely unlike Iron Man). He couldn&rsquo;t tell anyone in his lab what he was doing. &ldquo;I had a secret identity where I was driving an 8-foot-tall, half ton robot with an axe for a head.&rdquo; Although juggling all his responsibilities was tiring, his efforts did not go unnoticed.&nbsp;&ldquo;So many kids talk about how they look at us as super heroes.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Find Ross Mead on <a href="https://www.facebook.com/RossMead.RCL">Facebook</a> and <a href="https://twitter.com/RossMead">Twitter</a>.</p>
